body:
How to ruin a crobby shipper’s day

Gay marriage in South Dakota was legalized in 2015

Bobby (who lived in South Dakota) died in 2012

Unless you write a fix-it AU, these two couldn’t have been married officially where Bobby lives.

summary: I’ve no doubt the Good Omens fans have already dissected this quote to its roots: “Aziraphale ... had never done other to get...
body:
I’ve no doubt the Good Omens fans have already dissected this quote to its roots:

“Aziraphale … had never done other to get rid of demons than to hint to them very strongly that he, Aziraphale, had some work to be getting on with, and wasn’t it getting late? And Crowley had always got the hint,”

but it truly is one of my favorite moments in the entire book. The fact that by this account Crowley never once missed the hint, never let his desire to stay override Aziraphale’s wish to be alone, never treated his friend’s introversion as a personal slight, speaks worlds about how deeply Crowley understands and respects Aziraphale.

And I like to imagine that beyond his particular love for Aziraphale this is emblematic of Crowley’s approach to people in general. I rather get the sense that he hates the hegemony and strict expectations of heaven, inclining instead to value variety and individual need—even if respecting such things requires close attention and is not always entirely convenient.

After all, if there is one thing Crowley is good at it is recognizing and accepting nuance.

tags: i could have been an angel
summary: @hekate1308 Was browsing for some new music tonight, and came across this captivating song “I Could Have Been An Angel” by Sean...
body:
@hekate1308 Was browsing for some new music tonight, and came across this captivating song “I Could Have Been An Angel” by Sean McConnell. The chorus immediately made me think of your fic “Exchange,” where Crowley’s and Castiel’s relationships with the Winchesters are reversed. I still think from time to time about one particular scene:

Crow was… content. There was nothing of the usual demonic wrath that even plagued Crowley now and then, nothing of the wish for vengeance or the need to hurt others all those who were damned carried with them.

He concentrated on the book in his hands. It was easier.

That was such a poignant, painful moment. You know you’ve succeeded in your job as a writer when readers recall your work so vividly, and hear its echo in other places.
